defaultThe 2009 accident was caused by a catastrophic failure of the main gearbox which, in turn, caused the main rotor to separate from the 
defaulthelicopter.  The 2013 accident appears not to have been attributable to any mechanical malfunction and the helicopter was flown into the sea whilst on approach to Sumburgh airport.  The AAIB Bulletin on this accident appears to point to the possibility tha
defaultt the helicopter was allowed to enter a state of Vortex Ring, a low airspeed and almost vertical high rate of descent where the flow of air through the rotors re-circulates and the rate of descent increases and control is then lost.  Taking these two fatal
default accidents it would appear that the first was possibly due to a manufacturing and/or maintenance problem whilst the second may have been attributable
default to the
default pilots
default.  This is of course pure conjecture at this early stage in the investigation
default and the final A
defaultAIB report on the accident is now awaited.
